  "prompt": "Is the scheme of money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, the scheme of money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world, including China. Money laundering refers to the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This is typically done through a series of complex transactions or activities designed to obscure the origin of the funds.\n\nIn China, money laundering is explicitly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was enacted in 2007 and has been amended to strengthen enforcement. The law imposes strict penalties on individuals and entities involved in money laundering, including fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment. Chinese authorities, such as the People's Bank of China and the Ministry of Public Security, actively monitor and investigate suspicious financial activities to combat money laundering.\n\nGlobally, money laundering is also criminalized under various international agreements, such as the **United Nations Convention Against Corruption (UNCAC)** and the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** recommendations. Countries have implemented laws and regulations to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities to maintain the integrity of financial systems and combat organized crime, terrorism, and corruption.",
